The steps involved in the pair-wise similarity calculation phase are
outlined in Algorithm 1. The main input to the algorithm is a list of
records, 𝐑𝐑\mathbf{R}, which we aim to link and cluster (in our
case we aim to determine which birth records are by the same
mother). We assume each record has a unique numerical identifier,
r.i​dformulae-sequence𝑟𝑖𝑑r.id, and a time-stamp, r.tformulae-sequence𝑟𝑡r.t, which in our case is the
registration date of a birth certificate.
We use the list 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A} of attributes which we will compare
between records using the list of similarity functions 𝐒𝐒\mathbf{S}.
These are approximate string matching functions such as Jaro-Winkler
or edit distance (Christen, 2006), or functions specific to the content
of an attribute like a numerical year difference
function (Christen, 2012). We also provide a list of weights,
𝐰𝐰\mathbf{w}, to be assigned to the calculated similarities. The
value of the similarity sasubscript𝑠𝑎s_{a} for attribute a∈𝐀𝑎𝐀a\in\mathbf{A}
between two records risubscript𝑟𝑖r_{i} and rjsubscript𝑟𝑗r_{j} will be calculated as
sa​(ri,rj)=𝐒a​(ri,rj)⋅wasubscript𝑠𝑎subscript𝑟𝑖subscript𝑟𝑗⋅subscript𝐒𝑎subscript𝑟𝑖subscript𝑟𝑗subscript𝑤𝑎s_{a}(r_{i},r_{j})=\mathbf{S}_{a}(r_{i},r_{j})\cdot w_{a}, where wasubscript𝑤𝑎w_{a} is
the weight for attribute a∈𝐀𝑎𝐀a\in\mathbf{A} and 𝐒asubscript𝐒𝑎\mathbf{S}_{a} is
the similarity function used on a𝑎a. The attributes and corresponding
weight values we use in our experiments are shown in
Table 1 in Section 4.

We evaluate our proposed temporal clustering approaches using a
real Scottish birth data set that covers the population of the
Isle of Skye over the period from 1861 to 1901. This data set
contains 17,614 birth certificates, where each of these contains
personal information about the baby and its parents, as shown in
Table 1.

We implemented all techniques using Python 2.7.6 and used the
string matching functionalities provided in
Febrl (Christen, 2008) to conduct the pair-wise record
comparisons. We set the LSH min-hash parameters as b=100𝑏100b=100 (number
of bands) and r=4𝑟4r=4 (band size) in order to obtain a recall of
99.7%percent99.799.7\% of the true matches in the ground truth data set for the
similarity graph 𝐆𝐆\mathbf{G}.
We used three different subset of attributes, 𝐀𝐀\mathbf{A}, as
described in Algorithm 1 and illustrated in Table 1.
For details of the similarity functions used see (Christen, 2012).
We calculated attribute similarities with either the weights shown
in Table 1, or with all attribute weights set to 1.01.01.0.
We thus ended up with six similarity graphs where we set
sm​i​n=0.7subscript𝑠𝑚𝑖𝑛0.7s_{min}=0.7: weighted and no weights, and All
attributes, Parent names and addresses, and Parent
names only. This allows us to investigate how different ways to
calculate pair-wise similarities influence the quality of the final
clustering.

As with other historical data sets (Antonie
et al., 2014; Fu
et al., 2014b), this
birth data set has a very small number of unique name values (2,055
first names and only 547 last names). As Figure 3
shows, the frequency distributions of names are also very skewed.
The ten most common first and last name values occur in between
30%percent3030\% and 40%percent4040\% of all records, as Table 2
illustrates. Many records have missing values in address or
occupation attributes, and for unmarried women the details of a
baby’s father are mostly missing.
